# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: robin-hood-hashing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A **hash function** is any function that can be used to map data of arbitrary size to fixed-size values, though there are some hash functions that support variable-length output.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The values returned by a hash function are called *hash values*, *hash codes*, (*hash/message*) *digests*, or simply *hashes*.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The values are usually used to index a fixed-size table called a *hash table*.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Use of a hash function to index a hash table is called *hashing* or *scatter-storage addressing*.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions and their associated hash tables are used in data storage and retrieval applications to access data in a small and nearly constant time per retrieval.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] They require an amount of storage space only fractionally greater than the total space required for the data or records themselves.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Hashing is a way to access data quickly and efficiently.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Unlike lists or trees, it provides near-constant access time.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] It also uses much less storage than trying to store all possible keys directly, especially when keys are large or variable in length.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Use of hash functions relies on statistical properties of key and function interaction: worst-case behavior is intolerably bad but rare, and average-case behavior can be nearly optimal (minimal collision).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions are related to (and often confused with) checksums, check digits, fingerprints, lossy compression, randomization functions, error-correcting codes, and ciphers.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Although the concepts overlap to some extent, each one has its own uses and requirements and is designed and optimized differently.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The hash function differs from these concepts mainly in terms of data integrity.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Hash tables may use non-cryptographic hash functions, while cryptographic hash functions are used in cybersecurity to secure sensitive data such as passwords.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In a hash table, a hash function takes a key as an input, which is associated with a datum or record and used to identify it to the data storage and retrieval application.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The keys may be fixed-length, like an integer, or variable-length, like a name.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In some cases, the key is the datum itself.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The output is a hash code used to index a hash table holding the data or records, or pointers to them.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A good hash function satisfies two basic properties: it should be very fast to compute, and it should minimize duplication of output values (collisions).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions rely on generating favorable probability distributions for their effectiveness, reducing access time to nearly constant.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] High table loading factors, pathological key sets, and poorly designed hash functions can result in access times approaching linear in the number of items in the table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions can be designed to give the best worst-case performance, good performance under high table loading factors, and in special cases, perfect (collisionless) mapping of keys into hash codes.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Implementation is based on parity-preserving bit operations (XOR and ADD), multiply, or divide.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A necessary adjunct to the hash function is a collision-resolution method that employs an auxiliary data structure like linked lists, or systematic probing of the table to find an empty slot.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions are used in conjunction with hash tables to store and retrieve data items or data records.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The hash function translates the key associated with each datum or record into a hash code, which is used to index the hash table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] When an item is to be added to the table, the hash code may index an empty slot (also called a bucket), in which case the item is added to the table there.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] If the hash code indexes a full slot, then some kind of collision resolution is required: the new item may be omitted (not added to the table), or replace the old item, or be added to the table in some other location by a specified procedure.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] That procedure depends on the structure of the hash table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In *chained hashing*, each slot is the head of a linked list or chain, and items that collide at the slot are added to the chain.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Chains may be kept in random order and searched linearly, or in serial order, or as a self-ordering list by frequency to speed up access.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In *open address hashing*, the table is probed starting from the occupied slot in a specified manner, usually by linear probing, quadratic probing, or double hashing until an open slot is located or the entire table is probed (overflow).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Searching for the item follows the same procedure until the item is located, an open slot is found, or the entire table has been searched (item not in table).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions are also used to build caches for large data sets stored in slow media.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A cache is generally simpler than a hashed search table, since any collision can be resolved by discarding or writing back the older of the two colliding items.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions are an essential ingredient of the Bloom filter, a space-efficient probabilistic data structure that is used to test whether an element is a member of a set.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A special case of hashing is known as geometric hashing or the *grid method*.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In these applications, the set of all inputs is some sort of metric space, and the hashing function can be interpreted as a partition of that space into a grid of *cells*.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The table is often an array with two or more indices (called a *grid file*, *grid index*, *bucket grid*, and similar names), and the hash function returns an index tuple.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Hash tables are also used to implement associative arrays and dynamic sets.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A good hash function should map the expected inputs as evenly as possible over its output range.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] That is, every hash value in the output range should be generated with roughly the same probability.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The reason for this requirement is that the cost of hashing-based methods goes up sharply as the number of *collisions* — pairs of inputs that are mapped to the same hash value — increases.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] If some hash values are more likely to occur than others, then a larger fraction of the lookup operations will have to search through a larger set of colliding table entries.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This criterion only requires the value to be *uniformly distributed*, not *random* in any sense.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A good randomizing function is (barring computational efficiency concerns) generally a good choice as a hash function, but the converse need not be true.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Hash tables often contain only a small subset of the valid inputs.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] For instance, a club membership list may contain only a hundred or so member names, out of the very large set of all possible names.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In these cases, the uniformity criterion should hold for almost all typical subsets of entries that may be found in the table, not just for the global set of all possible entries.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In other words, if a typical set of *m* records is hashed to *n* table slots, then the probability of a bucket receiving many more than *m*/*n* records should be vanishingly small.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In particular, if *m* < *n*, then very few buckets should have more than one or two records.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A small number of collisions is virtually inevitable, even if *n* is much larger than *m*—see the birthday problem.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In special cases when the keys are known in advance and the key set is static, a hash function can be found that achieves absolute (or collisionless) uniformity.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Such a hash function is said to be *perfect*.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] There is no algorithmic way of constructing such a function—searching for one is a factorial function of the number of keys to be mapped versus the number of table slots that they are mapped into.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] When testing a hash function, the uniformity of the distribution of hash values can be evaluated by the chi-squared test.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This test is a goodness-of-fit measure: it is the actual distribution of items in buckets versus the expected (or uniform) distribution of items.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] where n is the number of keys, m is the number of buckets, and *b**j* is the number of items in bucket j.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A ratio within one confidence interval (such as 0.95 to 1.05) is indicative that the hash function evaluated has an expected uniform distribution.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions can have some technical properties that make it more likely that they will have a uniform distribution when applied.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] One is the strict avalanche criterion: whenever a single input bit is complemented, each of the output bits changes with a 50% probability.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The reason for this property is that selected subsets of the keyspace may have low variability.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] For the output to be uniformly distributed, a low amount of variability, even one bit, should translate into a high amount of variability (i.e. distribution over the tablespace) in the output.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Each bit should change with a probability of 50% because, if some bits are reluctant to change, then the keys become clustered around those values.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] If the bits want to change too readily, then the mapping is approaching a fixed XOR function of a single bit.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Standard tests for this property have been described in the literature.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The relevance of the criterion to a multiplicative hash function is assessed here.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In data storage and retrieval applications, the use of a hash function is a trade-off between search time and data storage space.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] If search time were unbounded, then a very compact unordered linear list would be the best medium; if storage space were unbounded, then a randomly accessible structure indexable by the key-value would be very large and very sparse, but very fast.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A hash function takes a finite amount of time to map a potentially large keyspace to a feasible amount of storage space searchable in a bounded amount of time regardless of the number of keys.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In most applications, the hash function should be computable with minimum latency and secondarily in a minimum number of instructions.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Computational complexity varies with the number of instructions required and latency of individual instructions, with the simplest being the bitwise methods (folding), followed by the multiplicative methods, and the most complex (slowest) are the division-based methods.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Because collisions should be infrequent, and cause a marginal delay but are otherwise harmless, it is usually preferable to choose a faster hash function over one that needs more computation but saves a few collisions.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Division-based implementations can be of particular concern because a division requires multiple cycles on nearly all processor microarchitectures.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Division (modulo) by a constant can be inverted to become a multiplication by the word-size multiplicative-inverse of that constant.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This can be done by the programmer, or by the compiler.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Division can also be reduced directly into a series of shift-subtracts and shift-adds, though minimizing the number of such operations required is a daunting problem; the number of machine-language instructions resulting may be more than a dozen and swamp the pipeline.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] If the microarchitecture has hardware multiply functional units, then the multiply-by-inverse is likely a better approach.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] We can allow the table size *n* to not be a power of 2 and still not have to perform any remainder or division operation, as these computations are sometimes costly.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] For example, let *n* be significantly less than 2*b*.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Consider a pseudorandom number generator function *P*(key) that is uniform on the interval [0, 2*b* − 1].
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A hash function uniform on the interval [0, *n* − 1] is *n* *P*(key) / 2*b*.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] We can replace the division by a (possibly faster) right bit shift: *n P*(key) >> *b*.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] If keys are being hashed repeatedly, and the hash function is costly, then computing time can be saved by precomputing the hash codes and storing them with the keys.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Matching hash codes almost certainly means that the keys are identical.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This technique is used for the transposition table in game-playing programs, which stores a 64-bit hashed representation of the board position.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A *universal hashing* scheme is a randomized algorithm that selects a hash function *h* among a family of such functions, in such a way that the probability of a collision of any two distinct keys is 1/*m*, where *m* is the number of distinct hash values desired—independently of the two keys.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Universal hashing ensures (in a probabilistic sense) that the hash function application will behave as well as if it were using a random function, for any distribution of the input data.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] It will, however, have more collisions than perfect hashing and may require more operations than a special-purpose hash function.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A hash function that allows only certain table sizes or strings only up to a certain length, or cannot accept a seed (i.e. allow double hashing) is less useful than one that does.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A hash function is applicable in a variety of situations.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A hash procedure must be deterministic—for a given input value, it must always generate the same hash value.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In other words, it must be a function of the data to be hashed, in the mathematical sense of the term.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This requirement excludes hash functions that depend on external variable parameters, such as pseudo-random number generators or the time of day.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] It also excludes functions that depend on the memory address of the object being hashed, because the address may change during execution (as may happen on systems that use certain methods of garbage collection), although sometimes rehashing of the item is possible.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The determinism is in the context of the reuse of the function.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] For example, Python adds the feature that hash functions make use of a randomized seed that is generated once when the Python process starts in addition to the input to be hashed.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The Python hash (SipHash) is still a valid hash function when used within a single run, but if the values are persisted (for example, written to disk), they can no longer be treated as valid hash values, since in the next run the random value might differ.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] It is often desirable that the output of a hash function have fixed size (but see below).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] If, for example, the output is constrained to 32-bit integer values, then the hash values can be used to index into an array.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Such hashing is commonly used to accelerate data searches.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Producing fixed-length output from variable-length input can be accomplished by breaking the input data into chunks of specific size.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions used for data searches use some arithmetic expression that iteratively processes chunks of the input (such as the characters in a string) to produce the hash value.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In many applications, the range of hash values may be different for each run of the program or may change along the same run (for instance, when a hash table needs to be expanded).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In those situations, one needs a hash function which takes two parameters—the input data *z*, and the number *n* of allowed hash values.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A common solution is to compute a fixed hash function with a very large range (say, 0 to 232 − 1), divide the result by *n*, and use the division's remainder.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] If *n* is itself a power of 2, this can be done by bit masking and bit shifting.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] When this approach is used, the hash function must be chosen so that the result has fairly uniform distribution between 0 and *n* − 1, for any value of *n* that may occur in the application.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Depending on the function, the remainder may be uniform only for certain values of *n*, e.g. odd or prime numbers.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] When the hash function is used to store values in a hash table that outlives the run of the program, and the hash table needs to be expanded or shrunk, the hash table is referred to as a dynamic hash table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A hash function that will relocate the minimum number of records when the table is resized is desirable.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] What is needed is a hash function *H*(*z*,*n*) (where *z* is the key being hashed and *n* is the number of allowed hash values) such that *H*(*z*,*n* + 1) = *H*(*z*,*n*) with probability close to *n*/(*n* + 1).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Linear hashing and spiral hashing are examples of dynamic hash functions that execute in constant time but relax the property of uniformity to achieve the minimal movement property.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Extendible hashing uses a dynamic hash function that requires space proportional to *n* to compute the hash function, and it becomes a function of the previous keys that have been inserted.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Several algorithms that preserve the uniformity property but require time proportional to *n* to compute the value of *H*(*z*,*n*) have been invented.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A hash function with minimal movement is especially useful in distributed hash tables.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In some applications, the input data may contain features that are irrelevant for comparison purposes.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] For example, when looking up a personal name, it may be desirable to ignore the distinction between upper and lower case letters.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] For such data, one must use a hash function that is compatible with the data equivalence criterion being used: that is, any two inputs that are considered equivalent must yield the same hash value.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This can be accomplished by normalizing the input before hashing it, as by upper-casing all letters.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] There are several common algorithms for hashing integers.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The method giving the best distribution is data-dependent.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] One of the simplest and most common methods in practice is the modulo division method.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] If the data to be hashed is small enough, then one can use the data itself (reinterpreted as an integer) as the hashed value.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The cost of computing this *identity* hash function is effectively zero.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This hash function is perfect, as it maps each input to a distinct hash value.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The meaning of "small enough" depends on the size of the type that is used as the hashed value.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] For example, in Java, the hash code is a 32-bit integer.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Thus the 32-bit integer `Integer` and 32-bit floating-point `Float` objects can simply use the value directly, whereas the 64-bit integer `Long` and 64-bit floating-point `Double` cannot.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Other types of data can also use this hashing scheme.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] For example, when mapping character strings between upper and lower case, one can use the binary encoding of each character, interpreted as an integer, to index a table that gives the alternative form of that character ("A" for "a", "8" for "8", etc.).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] If each character is stored in 8 bits (as in extended ASCII or ISO Latin 1), the table has only 28 = 256 entries; in the case of Unicode characters, the table would have 17 × 216 = 1114112 entries.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The same technique can be used to map two-letter country codes like "us" or "za" to country names (262 = 676 table entries), 5-digit ZIP codes like 13083 to city names (100000 entries), etc.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Invalid data values (such as the country code "xx" or the ZIP code 00000) may be left undefined in the table or mapped to some appropriate "null" value.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] If the keys are uniformly or sufficiently uniformly distributed over the key space, so that the key values are essentially random, then they may be considered to be already "hashed".
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In this case, any number of any bits in the key may be extracted and collated as an index into the hash table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] For example, a simple hash function might mask off the m least significant bits and use the result as an index into a hash table of size 2*m*.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A mid-squares hash code is produced by squaring the input and extracting an appropriate number of middle digits or bits.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] For example, if the input is 123456789 and the hash table size 10000, then squaring the key produces 15241578750190521, so the hash code is taken as the middle 4 digits of the 17-digit number (ignoring the high digit) 8750.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The mid-squares method produces a reasonable hash code if there is not a lot of leading or trailing zeros in the key.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This is a variant of multiplicative hashing, but not as good because an arbitrary key is not a good multiplier.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A standard technique is to use a modulo function on the key, by selecting a divisor M which is a prime number close to the table size, so *h*(*K*) ≡ *K* (mod *M*).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This gives a distribution from {0, *M* − 1}.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This gives good results over a large number of key sets.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A significant drawback of division hashing is that division requires multiple cycles on most modern architectures (including x86) and can be 10 times slower than multiplication.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A second drawback is that it will not break up clustered keys.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This technique works well in practice because many key sets are sufficiently random already, and the probability that a key set will be cyclical by a large prime number is small.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Algebraic coding is a variant of the division method of hashing which uses division by a polynomial modulo 2 instead of an integer to map n bits to m bits.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] If *Z*(*x*) is constructed to have t or fewer non-zero coefficients, then keys which share fewer than t bits are guaranteed to not collide.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Z is a function of k, t, and n (the last of which is a divisor of 2*k* − 1) and is constructed from the finite field GF(2*k*).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Define $P(x)=\prod _{j\in S}(x-\alpha ^{j})$ where α ∈*n* GF(2*k*) and where the coefficients of *P*(*x*) are computed in this field.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Since α2*j* is a root of *P*(*x*) whenever α*j* is a root, it follows that the coefficients *pi* of *P*(*x*) satisfy *p*2 *i* = *p*i, so they are all 0 or 1.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] If *R*(*x*) = *r**n*−1*x**n*−1 + ⋯ + *r*1*x* + *r*0 is any nonzero polynomial modulo 2 with at most t nonzero coefficients, then *R*(*x*) is not a multiple of *P*(*x*) modulo 2.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] If follows that the corresponding hash function will map keys with fewer than t bits in common to unique indices.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The usual outcome is that either n will get large, or t will get large, or both, for the scheme to be computationally feasible.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Therefore, it is more suited to hardware or microcode implementation.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Unique permutation hashing has a guaranteed best worst-case insertion time.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Standard multiplicative hashing uses the formula *h**a*(*K*) = ⌊(*aK* mod *W*) / (*W*/*M*)⌋, which produces a hash value in {0, …, *M* − 1}.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The value a is an appropriately chosen value that should be relatively prime to W; it should be large, and its binary representation a random mix of 1s and 0s.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] An important practical special case occurs when *W* = 2*w* and *M* = 2*m* are powers of 2 and w is the machine word size.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] and for fixed m and w this translates into a single integer multiplication and right-shift, making it one of the fastest hash functions to compute.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Multiplicative hashing is susceptible to a "common mistake" that leads to poor diffusion—higher-value input bits do not affect lower-value output bits.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A transmutation on the input which shifts the span of retained top bits down and XORs or ADDs them to the key before the multiplication step corrects for this.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Fibonacci hashing is a form of multiplicative hashing in which the multiplier is 2*w* / ϕ, where w is the machine word length and ϕ (phi) is the golden ratio (approximately 1.618).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A property of this multiplier is that it uniformly distributes over the table space, blocks of consecutive keys with respect to any block of bits in the key.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Consecutive keys within the high bits or low bits of the key (or some other field) are relatively common.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The multiplier should be odd, so the least significant bit of the output is invertible modulo 2*w*.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The last two values given above are rounded (up and down, respectively) by more than 1/2 of a least-significant bit to achieve this.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Zobrist hashing was originally introduced as a means of compactly representing chess positions in computer game-playing programs.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A unique random number was assigned to represent each type of piece (six each for black and white) on each space of the board.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Thus a table of 64×12 such numbers is initialized at the start of the program.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The random numbers could be any length, but 64 bits was natural due to the 64 squares on the board.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A position was transcribed by cycling through the pieces in a position, indexing the corresponding random numbers (vacant spaces were not included in the calculation) and XORing them together (the starting value could be 0 (the identity value for XOR) or a random seed).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The resulting value was reduced by modulo, folding, or some other operation to produce a hash table index.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The original Zobrist hash was stored in the table as the representation of the position.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Later, the method was extended to hashing integers by representing each byte in each of 4 possible positions in the word by a unique 32-bit random number.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Thus, a table of 28×4 random numbers is constructed.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A 32-bit hashed integer is transcribed by successively indexing the table with the value of each byte of the plain text integer and XORing the loaded values together (again, the starting value can be the identity value or a random seed).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The natural extension to 64-bit integers is by use of a table of 28×8 64-bit random numbers.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This kind of function has some nice theoretical properties, one of which is called *3-tuple independence*, meaning that every 3-tuple of keys is equally likely to be mapped to any 3-tuple of hash values.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A hash function can be designed to exploit existing entropy in the keys.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] If the keys have leading or trailing zeros, or particular fields that are unused, always zero or some other constant, or generally vary little, then masking out only the volatile bits and hashing on those will provide a better and possibly faster hash function.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Selected divisors or multipliers in the division and multiplicative schemes may make more uniform hash functions if the keys are cyclic or have other redundancies.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] When the data values are long (or variable-length) character strings—such as personal names, web page addresses, or mail messages—their distribution is usually very uneven, with complicated dependencies.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] For example, text in any natural language has highly non-uniform distributions of characters, and character pairs, characteristic of the language.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] For such data, it is prudent to use a hash function that depends on all characters of the string—and depends on each character in a different way.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Simplistic hash functions may add the first and last *n* characters of a string along with the length, or form a word-size hash from the middle 4 characters of a string.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This saves iterating over the (potentially long) string, but hash functions that do not hash on all characters of a string can readily become linear due to redundancies, clustering, or other pathologies in the key set.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Such strategies may be effective as a custom hash function if the structure of the keys is such that either the middle, ends, or other fields are zero or some other invariant constant that does not differentiate the keys; then the invariant parts of the keys can be ignored.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The paradigmatic example of folding by characters is to add up the integer values of all the characters in the string.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A better idea is to multiply the hash total by a constant, typically a sizable prime number, before adding in the next character, ignoring overflow.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Using exclusive-or instead of addition is also a plausible alternative.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The final operation would be a modulo, mask, or other function to reduce the word value to an index the size of the table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The weakness of this procedure is that information may cluster in the upper or lower bits of the bytes; this clustering will remain in the hashed result and cause more collisions than a proper randomizing hash.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] ASCII byte codes, for example, have an upper bit of 0, and printable strings do not use the last byte code or most of the first 32 byte codes, so the information, which uses the remaining byte codes, is clustered in the remaining bits in an unobvious manner.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The classic approach, dubbed the PJW hash based on the work of Peter J.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Weinberger at Bell Labs in the 1970s, was originally designed for hashing identifiers into compiler symbol tables as given in the "Dragon Book".
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This hash function offsets the bytes 4 bits before adding them together.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] When the quantity wraps, the high 4 bits are shifted out and if non-zero, xored back into the low byte of the cumulative quantity.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The result is a word-size hash code to which a modulo or other reducing operation can be applied to produce the final hash index.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Today, especially with the advent of 64-bit word sizes, much more efficient variable-length string hashing by word chunks is available.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The final word, which may have unoccupied byte positions, is filled with zeros or a specified randomizing value before being folded into the hash.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The accumulated hash code is reduced by a final modulo or other operation to yield an index into the table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Analogous to the way an ASCII or EBCDIC character string representing a decimal number is converted to a numeric quantity for computing, a variable-length string can be converted as *x**k*−1a*k*−1 + *x**k*−2a*k*−2 + ⋯ + *x*1*a* + *x*0.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This is simply a polynomial in a radix *a* > 1 that takes the components (*x*0,*x*1,...,*x**k*−1) as the characters of the input string of length *k*.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] It can be used directly as the hash code, or a hash function applied to it to map the potentially large value to the hash table size.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The value of *a* is usually a prime number large enough to hold the number of different characters in the character set of potential keys.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Radix conversion hashing of strings minimizes the number of collisions.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Available data sizes may restrict the maximum length of string that can be hashed with this method.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] For example, a 128-bit word will hash only a 26-character alphabetic string (ignoring case) with a radix of 29; a printable ASCII string is limited to 9 characters using radix 97 and a 64-bit word.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] However, alphabetic keys are usually of modest length, because keys must be stored in the hash table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Numeric character strings are usually not a problem; 64 bits can count up to 1019, or 19 decimal digits with radix 10.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] In some applications, such as substring search, one can compute a hash function *h* for every *k*-character substring of a given *n*-character string by advancing a window of width *k* characters along the string, where *k* is a fixed integer, and *n* > *k*.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The straightforward solution, which is to extract such a substring at every character position in the text and compute *h* separately, requires a number of operations proportional to *k*·*n*.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] However, with the proper choice of *h*, one can use the technique of rolling hash to compute all those hashes with an effort proportional to *mk* + *n* where *m* is the number of occurrences of the substring.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The hash function used for the algorithm is usually the Rabin fingerprint, designed to avoid collisions in 8-bit character strings, but other suitable hash functions are also used.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing, also known as similarity hashing, is a technique for detecting data that is similar, but not exactly the same, as other data.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hash functions, which are designed to have significantly different hashes for even minor differences.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing has been used to identify malware and has potential for other applications, like data loss prevention and detecting multiple versions of code.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Perceptual hashing is the use of a fingerprinting algorithm that produces a snippet, hash, or fingerprint of various forms of multimedia.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] A perceptual hash is a type of locality-sensitive hash, which is analogous if features of the multimedia are similar.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hashing, which relies on the avalanche effect of a small change in input value creating a drastic change in output value.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Perceptual hash functions are widely used in finding cases of online copyright infringement as well as in digital forensics because of the ability to have a correlation between hashes so similar data can be found (for instance with a differing watermark).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] Worst case results for a hash function can be assessed two ways: theoretical and practical.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The theoretical worst case is the probability that all keys map to a single slot.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The practical worst case is the expected longest probe sequence (hash function + collision resolution method).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] This analysis considers uniform hashing, that is, any key will map to any particular slot with probability 1/*m*, a characteristic of universal hash functions.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] While Knuth worries about adversarial attack on real time systems, Gonnet has shown that the probability of such a case is "ridiculously small".
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] His representation was that the probability of *k* of *n* keys mapping to a single slot is α*k* / (*e*α *k*!), where *α* is the load factor, *n*/*m*.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-function] The term *hash* offers a natural analogy with its non-technical meaning (to chop up or make a mess out of something), given how hash functions scramble their input data to derive their output.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] In computer science, a **hash table** is a data structure that implements an associative array, also called a **dictionary** or simply **map**; an associative array is an abstract data type that maps keys to values.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] A hash table uses a hash function to compute an *index*, also called a *hash code*, into an array of *buckets* or *slots*, from which the desired value can be found.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] During lookup, the key is hashed and the resulting hash indicates where the corresponding value is stored.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] A map implemented by a hash table is called a **hash map**.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Most hash table designs employ an imperfect hash function.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Hash collisions, where the hash function generates the same index for more than one key, therefore typically must be accommodated in some way.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Common strategies to handle hash collisions include chaining, which stores multiple elements in the same slot using linked lists, and open addressing, which searches for the next available slot according to a probing sequence.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] In a well-dimensioned hash table, the average time complexity for each lookup is independent of the number of elements stored in the table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Many hash table designs also allow arbitrary insertions and deletions of key–value pairs, at amortized constant average cost per operation.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Hashing is an example of a space–time tradeoff.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] If memory is infinite, the entire key can be used directly as an index to locate its value with a single memory access.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] On the other hand, if infinite time is available, values can be stored without regard for their keys, and a binary search or linear search can be used to retrieve the element.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] In many situations, hash tables turn out to be on average more efficient than search trees or any other table lookup structure.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] For this reason, they are widely used in many kinds of computer software, particularly for associative arrays, database indexing, caches, and sets.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Many programming languages provide built-in hash table structures, such as Python’s dictionaries, Java’s HashMap, C++’s unordered_map, Go maps, which abstract the complexity of hashing from the programmer.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The idea of hashing arose independently in different places.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] In January 1953, Hans Peter Luhn wrote an internal IBM memorandum that used hashing with chaining.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The first example of open addressing was proposed by A.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Around the same time, Gene Amdahl, Elaine M.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] McGraw, Nathaniel Rochester, and Arthur Samuel of IBM Research implemented hashing for the IBM 701 assembler.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Open addressing with linear probing is credited to Amdahl, although Andrey Ershov independently had the same idea.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The term "open addressing" was coined by W.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Wesley Peterson in his article which discusses the problem of search in large files.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The first published work on hashing with chaining is credited to Arnold Dumey, who discussed the idea of using remainder modulo a prime as a hash function.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The word "hashing" was first published in an article by Robert Morris.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] A theoretical analysis of linear probing was submitted originally by Konheim and Weiss.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] An associative array stores a set of (key, value) pairs and allows insertion, deletion, and lookup (search), with the constraint of unique keys.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] In the hash table implementation of associative arrays, an array A of length m is partially filled with n elements, where $m\geq n$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] A key **x** is hashed using a hash function h to compute an index location $A[h(x)]$ in the hash table, where $h(x)<m$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The efficiency of a hash table depends on the load factor, defined as the ratio of the number of stored elements to the number of available slots, with lower load factors generally yielding faster operations.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] At this index, both the key and its associated value are stored.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Storing the key alongside the value ensures that lookups can verify the key at the index to retrieve the correct value, even in the presence of collisions.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Under reasonable assumptions, hash tables have better time complexity bounds on search, delete, and insert operations in comparison to self-balancing binary search trees.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Hash tables are also commonly used to implement sets, by omitting the stored value for each key and merely tracking whether the key is present.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The performance of the hash table deteriorates in relation to the load factor $\alpha$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] In the limit of large m and n , each bucket statistically has a Poisson distribution with expectation $\lambda =\alpha$ for an ideally random hash function.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The software typically ensures that the load factor $\alpha$ remains below a certain constant, $\alpha _{\max }$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Therefore, a common approach is to resize or "rehash" the hash table whenever the load factor $\alpha$ reaches $\alpha _{\max }$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Similarly the table may also be resized if the load factor drops below $\alpha _{\max }/4$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] With separate chaining hash tables, each slot of the bucket array stores a pointer to a list or array of data.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Separate chaining hash tables suffer gradually declining performance as the load factor grows, and no fixed point beyond which resizing is absolutely needed.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] With separate chaining, the value of $\alpha _{\max }$ that gives best performance is typically between 1 and 3.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] With open addressing, each slot of the bucket array holds exactly one item.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Therefore an open-addressed hash table cannot have a load factor greater than 1.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The performance of open addressing becomes very bad when the load factor approaches 1.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Therefore a hash table that uses open addressing *must* be resized or *rehashed* if the load factor $\alpha$ approaches 1.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] With open addressing, acceptable figures of max load factor $\alpha _{\max }$ should range around 0.6 to 0.75.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] A hash function $h:U\rightarrow \{0,...,m-1\}$ maps the universe U of keys to indices or slots within the table, that is, $h(x)\in \{0,...,m-1\}$ for $x\in U$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The conventional implementations of hash functions are based on the *integer universe assumption* that all elements of the table stem from the universe $U=\{0,...,u-1\}$ , where the bit length of u is confined within the word size of a computer architecture.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] A hash function h is said to be perfect for a given set S if it is injective on S , that is, if each element $x\in S$ maps to a different value in ${0,...,m-1}$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] A perfect hash function can be created if all the keys are known ahead of time.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The schemes of hashing used in *integer universe assumption* include hashing by division, hashing by multiplication, universal hashing, dynamic perfect hashing, and static perfect hashing.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] However, hashing by division is the commonly used scheme.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The scheme in hashing by division is as follows: $h(x)\ =\ x\,{\bmod {\,}}m,$ where $h(x)$ is the hash value of $x\in S$ and m is the size of the table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The scheme in hashing by multiplication is as follows: $h(x)=\lfloor m{\bigl (}(xA){\bmod {1}}{\bigr )}\rfloor$ Where A is a non-integer real-valued constant and m is the size of the table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] An advantage of the hashing by multiplication is that the m is not critical.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Although any value A produces a hash function, Donald Knuth suggests using the golden ratio.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Commonly a string is used as a key to the hash function.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The third edition of *The C++ Programming Language* describes a simple hash function in which an unsigned integer that is initially zero is repeatedly left shifted one bit and then xor'ed with the integer value of the next character.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] This hash value is then taken modulo the table size.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] If the left shift is not circular, then the string length should be at least eight bits less than the size of the unsigned integer in bits.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Another common way to hash a string to an integer is with a polynomial rolling hash function.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Uniform distribution of the hash values is a fundamental requirement of a hash function.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] A non-uniform distribution increases the number of collisions and the cost of resolving them.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Uniformity is sometimes difficult to ensure by design, but may be evaluated empirically using statistical tests, e.g., a Pearson's chi-squared test for discrete uniform distributions.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The distribution needs to be uniform only for table sizes that occur in the application.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] In particular, if one uses dynamic resizing with exact doubling and halving of the table size, then the hash function needs to be uniform only when the size is a power of two.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Here the index can be computed as some range of bits of the hash function.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] On the other hand, some hashing algorithms prefer to have the size be a prime number.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] For open addressing schemes, the hash function should also avoid *runs*, the mapping of two or more keys to consecutive slots.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Such runs may cause the lookup cost to skyrocket, even if the load factor is low and collisions are infrequent.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The popular multiplicative hash is claimed to have particularly poor run behavior.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] K-independent hashing offers a way to prove a certain hash function does not have bad keysets for a given type of hashtable.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] A number of K-independence results are known for collision resolution schemes such as linear probing and cuckoo hashing.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Since K-independence can prove a hash function works, one can then focus on finding the fastest possible such hash function.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] A search algorithm that uses hashing consists of two parts.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The first part is computing a hash function which transforms the search key into an array index.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The ideal case is such that no two search keys hash to the same array index.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] However, this is not always the case and impossible to guarantee for unseen given data.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Hence the second part of the algorithm is collision resolution.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The two common methods for collision resolution are separate chaining and open addressing.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] In separate chaining, the process involves building a linked list with key–value pair for each search array index.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The collided items are chained together through a single linked list, which can be traversed to access the item with a unique search key.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Collision resolution through chaining with linked list is a common method of implementation of hash tables.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] If the element is comparable either numerically or lexically, and inserted into the list by maintaining the total order, it results in faster termination of the unsuccessful searches.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] If the keys are ordered, it could be efficient to use "self-organizing" concepts such as using a self-balancing binary search tree, through which the theoretical worst case could be brought down to $O(\log {n})$ , although it introduces additional complexities.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] In dynamic perfect hashing, two-level hash tables are used to reduce the look-up complexity to be a guaranteed $O(1)$ in the worst case.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] In this technique, the buckets of k entries are organized as perfect hash tables with $k^{2}$ slots providing constant worst-case lookup time, and low amortized time for insertion.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] A study shows array-based separate chaining to be 97% more performant when compared to the standard linked list method under heavy load.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Techniques such as using fusion tree for each buckets also result in constant time for all operations with high probability.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The linked list of separate chaining implementation may not be cache-conscious due to spatial locality—locality of reference—when the nodes of the linked list are scattered across memory, thus the list traversal during insert and search may entail CPU cache inefficiencies.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Open addressing is another collision resolution technique in which every entry record is stored in the bucket array itself, and the hash resolution is performed through **probing**.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] When a new entry has to be inserted, the buckets are examined, starting with the hashed-to slot and proceeding in some *probe sequence*, until an unoccupied slot is found.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] When searching for an entry, the buckets are scanned in the same sequence, until either the target record is found, or an unused array slot is found, which indicates an unsuccessful search.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The performance of open addressing may be slower compared to separate chaining since the probe sequence increases when the load factor $\alpha$ approaches 1.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The probing results in an infinite loop if the load factor reaches 1, in the case of a completely filled table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The average cost of linear probing depends on the hash function's ability to distribute the elements uniformly throughout the table to avoid runs, since formation of runs would result in increased search time.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Since the slots are located in successive locations, linear probing could lead to better utilization of CPU cache due to locality of references resulting in reduced memory latency.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Coalesced hashing is a hybrid of both separate chaining and open addressing in which the buckets or nodes link within the table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The algorithm is ideally suited for fixed memory allocation.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The collision in coalesced hashing is resolved by identifying the largest-indexed empty slot on the hash table, then the colliding value is inserted into that slot.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The bucket is also linked to the inserted node's slot which contains its colliding hash address.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Cuckoo hashing is a form of open addressing collision resolution technique which guarantees $O(1)$ worst-case lookup complexity and constant amortized time for insertions.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The collision is resolved through maintaining two hash tables, each having its own hashing function, and collided slot gets replaced with the given item, and the preoccupied element of the slot gets displaced into the other hash table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The process continues until every key has its own spot in the empty buckets of the tables; if the procedure enters into infinite loop—which is identified through maintaining a threshold loop counter—both hash tables get rehashed with newer hash functions and the procedure continues.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Hopscotch hashing is an open addressing based algorithm which combines the elements of cuckoo hashing, linear probing and chaining through the notion of a *neighbourhood* of buckets—the subsequent buckets around any given occupied bucket, also called a "virtual" bucket.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The algorithm is designed to deliver better performance when the load factor of the hash table grows beyond 90%; it also provides high throughput in concurrent settings, thus well suited for implementing resizable concurrent hash table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Each bucket within the hash table includes an additional "hop-information"—an *H*-bit bit array for indicating the relative distance of the item which was originally hashed into the current virtual bucket within *H* − 1 entries.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] *H* − 1, subsequent swap and hop-info bit array manipulation of each bucket is performed in accordance with its neighbourhood invariant properties.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Robin Hood hashing is an open addressing based collision resolution algorithm; the collisions are resolved through favouring the displacement of the element that is farthest—or longest *probe sequence length* (PSL)—from its "home location" i.e. the bucket to which the item was hashed into.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] It is named after Robin Hood, a mythical heroic outlaw who stole from the rich to give to the poor.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Although Robin Hood hashing does not change the theoretical search cost, it significantly affects the variance of the distribution of the items on the buckets, i.e. dealing with long run formation in the hash table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Each node within the hash table that uses Robin Hood hashing should be augmented to store an extra PSL value.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] If a hash table becomes "too empty" after deleting some elements, resizing may be performed to avoid excessive memory usage.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Generally, a new hash table with a size double that of the original hash table gets allocated privately and every item in the original hash table gets moved to the newly allocated one by computing the hash values of the items followed by the insertion operation.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Rehashing is simple, but computationally expensive.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Some hash table implementations, notably in real-time systems, cannot pay the price of enlarging the hash table all at once, because it may interrupt time-critical operations.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] If one cannot avoid dynamic resizing, a solution is to perform the resizing gradually to avoid storage blip—typically at 50% of new table's size—during rehashing and to avoid memory fragmentation that triggers heap compaction due to deallocation of large memory blocks caused by the old hash table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] In such case, the rehashing operation is done incrementally through extending prior memory block allocated for the old hash table such that the buckets of the hash table remain unaltered.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] A common approach for amortized rehashing involves maintaining two hash functions $h_{\text{old}}$ and $h_{\text{new}}$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Linear hashing is an implementation of the hash table which enables dynamic growths or shrinks of the table one bucket at a time.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The performance of a hash table is dependent on the hash function's ability in generating quasi-random numbers ( $\sigma$ ) for entries in the hash table where K , n and $h(x)$ denotes the key, number of buckets and the hash function such that $\sigma \ =\ h(K)\ \%\ n$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] If the hash function generates the same $\sigma$ for distinct keys ( $K_{1}\neq K_{2},\ h(K_{1})\ =\ h(K_{2})$ ), this results in *collision*, which is dealt with in a variety of ways.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The constant time complexity ( $O(1)$ ) of the operation in a hash table is presupposed on the condition that the hash function doesn't generate colliding indices; thus, the performance of the hash table is directly proportional to the chosen hash function's ability to disperse the indices.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] However, construction of such a hash function is practically infeasible, that being so, implementations depend on case-specific collision resolution techniques in achieving higher performance.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] The best performance is obtained in the case that the hash function distributes the elements of the universe uniformaly, and the elements stored at the table are drawn at random from the universe.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] In this case, in hashing with chaining, the expected time for a successful search is ${\textstyle 1+{\frac {\alpha }{2}}+\Theta \left({\frac {1}{m}}\right)}$ , and the expected time for an unsuccessful search is ${\textstyle e^{-\alpha }+\alpha +\Theta \left({\frac {1}{m}}\right)}$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Hash tables are commonly used to implement many types of in-memory tables.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] They are used to implement associative arrays.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Hash tables may also be used as disk-based data structures and database indices (such as in dbm) although B-trees are more popular in these applications.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Hash tables can be used to implement caches, auxiliary data tables that are used to speed up the access to data that is primarily stored in slower media.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] In this application, hash collisions can be handled by discarding one of the two colliding entries—usually erasing the old item that is currently stored in the table and overwriting it with the new item, so every item in the table has a unique hash value.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Hash tables can be used in the implementation of set data structure, which can store unique values without any particular order; set is typically used in testing the membership of a value in the collection, rather than element retrieval.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] A transposition table to a complex Hash Table which stores information about each section that has been searched.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/hash-table] Many programming languages provide hash table functionality, either as built-in associative arrays or as standard library modules.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Along with quadratic probing and double hashing, linear probing is a form of open addressing.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] In these schemes, each cell of a hash table stores a single key–value pair.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] When the hash function causes a collision by mapping a new key to a cell of the hash table that is already occupied by another key, linear probing searches the table for the closest following free location and inserts the new key there.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Lookups are performed in the same way, by searching the table sequentially starting at the position given by the hash function, until finding a cell with a matching key or an empty cell.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] It takes constant expected time per search, insertion, or deletion when implemented using a random hash function, a 5-independent hash function, or tabulation hashing.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Good results can also be achieved in practice with other hash functions such as MurmurHash.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Linear probing is a component of open addressing schemes for using a hash table to solve the dictionary problem.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] In the dictionary problem, a data structure should maintain a collection of key–value pairs subject to operations that insert or delete pairs from the collection or that search for the value associated with a given key.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] In open addressing solutions to this problem, the data structure is an array T (the hash table) whose cells *T*[*i*] (when nonempty) each store a single key–value pair.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] A hash function is used to map each key into the cell of T where that key should be stored, typically scrambling the keys so that keys with similar values are not placed near each other in the table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] A hash collision occurs when the hash function maps a key into a cell that is already occupied by a different key.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Linear probing is a strategy for resolving collisions, by placing the new key into the closest following empty cell.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] To search for a given key x, the cells of T are examined, beginning with the cell at index *h*(*x*) (where h is the hash function) and continuing to the adjacent cells *h*(*x*) + 1, *h*(*x*) + 2, ..., until finding either an empty cell or a cell whose stored key is x.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] If a cell containing the key is found, the search returns the value from that cell.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Otherwise, if an empty cell is found, the key cannot be in the table, because it would have been placed in that cell in preference to any later cell that has not yet been searched.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] In this case, the search returns as its result that the key is not present in the dictionary.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] To insert a key–value pair (*x*,*v*) into the table (possibly replacing any existing pair with the same key), the insertion algorithm follows the same sequence of cells that would be followed for a search, until finding either an empty cell or a cell whose stored key is x.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] The new key–value pair is then placed into that cell.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] If the insertion would cause the load factor of the table (its fraction of occupied cells) to grow above some preset threshold, the whole table may be replaced by a new table, larger by a constant factor, with a new hash function, as in a dynamic array.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Setting this threshold close to zero and using a high growth rate for the table size leads to faster hash table operations but greater memory usage than threshold values close to one and low growth rates.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] A common choice would be to double the table size when the load factor would exceed 1/2, causing the load factor to stay between 1/4 and 1/2.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] It is also possible to remove a key–value pair from the dictionary.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] However, it is not sufficient to do so by simply emptying its cell.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] This would affect searches for other keys that have a hash value earlier than the emptied cell, but that are stored in a position later than the emptied cell.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] The emptied cell would cause those searches to incorrectly report that the key is not present.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Instead, when a cell i is emptied, it is necessary to search forward through the following cells of the table until finding either another empty cell or a key that can be moved to cell i (that is, a key whose hash value is equal to or earlier than i).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] When an empty cell is found, then emptying cell i is safe and the deletion process terminates.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] But, when the search finds a key that can be moved to cell i, it performs this move.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] This has the effect of speeding up later searches for the moved key, but it also empties out another cell, later in the same block of occupied cells.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] The search for a movable key continues for the new emptied cell, in the same way, until it terminates by reaching a cell that was already empty.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] In this process of moving keys to earlier cells, each key is examined only once.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Therefore, the time to complete the whole process is proportional to the length of the block of occupied cells containing the deleted key, matching the running time of the other hash table operations.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Alternatively, it is possible to use a lazy deletion strategy in which a key–value pair is removed by replacing the value by a special flag value indicating a deleted key.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] However, these flag values will contribute to the load factor of the hash table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] With this strategy, it may become necessary to clean the flag values out of the array and rehash all the remaining key–value pairs once too large a fraction of the array becomes occupied by deleted keys.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Linear probing provides good locality of reference, which causes it to require few uncached memory accesses per operation.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Because of this, for low to moderate load factors, it can provide very high performance.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] However, compared to some other open addressing strategies, its performance degrades more quickly at high load factors because of primary clustering, a tendency for one collision to cause more nearby collisions.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Additionally, achieving good performance with this method requires a higher-quality hash function than for some other collision resolution schemes.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Using linear probing, dictionary operations can be implemented in constant expected time.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] In other words, insert, remove and search operations can be implemented in O(1), as long as the load factor of the hash table is a constant strictly less than one.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] In more detail, the time for any particular operation (a search, insertion, or deletion) is proportional to the length of the contiguous block of occupied cells at which the operation starts.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] If all starting cells are equally likely, in a hash table with N cells, then a maximal block of k occupied cells will have probability *k*/*N* of containing the starting location of a search, and will take time *O*(*k*) whenever it is the starting location.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Therefore, the expected time for an operation can be calculated as the product of these two terms, *O*(*k*2/*N*), summed over all of the maximal blocks of contiguous cells in the table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] This formula can be simplified by replacing Block(*i*,*k*) by a simpler necessary condition Full(*k*), the event that at least k elements have hash values that lie within a block of cells of length k.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] After this replacement, the value within the sum no longer depends on i, and the 1/*N* factor cancels the N terms of the outer summation.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] But by the multiplicative form of the Chernoff bound, when the load factor is bounded away from one, the probability that a block of length k contains at least k hashed values is exponentially small as a function of k, causing this sum to be bounded by a constant independent of n.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] It is also possible to perform the same analysis using Stirling's approximation instead of the Chernoff bound to estimate the probability that a block contains exactly k hashed values.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] In terms of the load factor α, the expected time to perform a successful search on a random key is *O*(1 + 1/(1 − *α*)), and the expected time to perform an unsuccessful search (or the insertion of a new key) is *O*(1 + 1/(1 − *α*)2).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] For constant load factors, with high probability, the longest probe sequence (among the probe sequences for all keys stored in the table) has logarithmic length.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Linear probing hash tables suffer from a problem known as primary clustering, in which elements to group together into long contiguous runs.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] In terms of the load factor α, the expected length of the run containing a given element is $\Theta (1+1/(1-\alpha )^{2})$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] This is why insertions take time $\Theta (1+1/(1-\alpha )^{2})$ , as opposed to the running time of $\Theta (1+1/(1-\alpha ))$ achieved by other open-addressed hash tables such as uniform probing and double hashing.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Primary clustering also affects unsuccessful searches, since like insertions, they must travel to the end of a run.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Some variations of linear probing are able to achieve better bounds for unsuccessful searches and insertions, by using techniques that reduce primary clustering.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Because linear probing is especially sensitive to unevenly distributed hash values, it is important to combine it with a high-quality hash function that does not produce such irregularities.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] The analysis above assumes that each key's hash is a random number independent of the hashes of all the other keys.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] This assumption is unrealistic for most applications of hashing.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] However, random or pseudorandom hash values may be used when hashing objects by their identity rather than by their value.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] For instance, this is done using linear probing by the IdentityHashMap class of the Java collections framework.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] The hash value that this class associates with each object, its identityHashCode, is guaranteed to remain fixed for the lifetime of an object but is otherwise arbitrary.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Because the identityHashCode is constructed only once per object, and is not required to be related to the object's address or value, its construction may involve slower computations such as the call to a random or pseudorandom number generator.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] For instance, Java 8 uses an Xorshift pseudorandom number generator to construct these values.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] For most applications of hashing, it is necessary to compute the hash function for each value every time that it is hashed, rather than once when its object is created.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] In such applications, random or pseudorandom numbers cannot be used as hash values, because then different objects with the same value would have different hashes.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] And cryptographic hash functions (which are designed to be computationally indistinguishable from truly random functions) are usually too slow to be used in hash tables.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Instead, other methods for constructing hash functions have been devised.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] These methods compute the hash function quickly, and can be proven to work well with linear probing.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] In particular, linear probing has been analyzed from the framework of k-independent hashing, a class of hash functions that are initialized from a small random seed and that are equally likely to map any k-tuple of distinct keys to any k-tuple of indexes.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] The parameter k can be thought of as a measure of hash function quality: the larger k is, the more time it will take to compute the hash function but it will behave more similarly to completely random functions.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] For linear probing, 5-independence is enough to guarantee constant expected time per operation, while some 4-independent hash functions perform badly, taking up to logarithmic time per operation.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Another method of constructing hash functions with both high quality and practical speed is tabulation hashing.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] In this method, the hash value for a key is computed by using each byte of the key as an index into a table of random numbers (with a different table for each byte position).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] The numbers from those table cells are then combined by a bitwise exclusive or operation.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Hash functions constructed this way are only 3-independent.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Nevertheless, linear probing using these hash functions takes constant expected time per operation.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Both tabulation hashing and standard methods for generating 5-independent hash functions are limited to keys that have a fixed number of bits.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] To handle strings or other types of variable-length keys, it is possible to compose a simpler universal hashing technique that maps the keys to intermediate values and a higher quality (5-independent or tabulation) hash function that maps the intermediate values to hash table indices.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] They point out that each table look-up require several cycles, being more expensive than simple arithmetic operations.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] They also found MurmurHash to be superior than tabulation hashing: "By studying the results provided by Mult and Murmur, we think that the trade-off for by tabulation (...) is less attractive in practice".
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] The idea of an associative array that allows data to be accessed by its value rather than by its address dates back to the mid-1940s in the work of Konrad Zuse and Vannevar Bush, but hash tables were not described until 1953, in an IBM memorandum by Hans Peter Luhn.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Luhn used a different collision resolution method, chaining, rather than linear probing.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Knuth (1963) summarizes the early history of linear probing.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] It was the first open addressing method, and was originally synonymous with open addressing.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] According to Knuth, it was first used by Gene Amdahl, Elaine M.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] McGraw (née Boehme), and Arthur Samuel in 1954, in an assembler program for the IBM 701 computer.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] The first published description of linear probing is by Peterson (1957), who also credits Samuel, Amdahl, and Boehme but adds that "the system is so natural, that it very likely may have been conceived independently by others either before or since that time".
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Another early publication of this method was by Soviet researcher Andrey Ershov, in 1958.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] The first theoretical analysis of linear probing, showing that it takes constant expected time per operation with random hash functions, was given by Knuth.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Sedgewick calls Knuth's work "a landmark in the analysis of algorithms".
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Knuth's original analysis was never formally published, and the first published analysis was due to Konheim and Weiss in 1966.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Knuth's analysis disproved an earlier conjecture by Peterson that, at load factor $\alpha =1-\varepsilon$ , the expected time per insertion should be $\Theta (1+\varepsilon ^{-1})$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Knuth showed instead that the time per operation grows as at a rate of $\Theta (1+\varepsilon ^{-2})$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] This effect, in which the insertion time grows quadratically faster than one might intuitively guess, became known as primary clustering.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Subsequent work has introduced several algorithmic techniques to reduce primary clustering, including a variation of linear probing known as graveyard hashing that achieves the ideal bound of $\Theta (1+\varepsilon ^{-1})$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/linear-probing] Other later developments include a more detailed analysis of the probability distribution of the running time, amortized analyses for workloads with both insertions and deletions, and analyses of linear probing using explicit families of hash functions.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] in which the interval between probes is fixed — often set to 1.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] The main trade offs between these methods are that linear probing has the best cache performance but is most sensitive to clustering, while double hashing has poor cache performance but exhibits virtually no clustering; quadratic probing falls in between in both areas.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] Double hashing can also require more computation than other forms of probing.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] Some open addressing methods, such as Hopscotch hashing, Robin Hood hashing, last-come-first-served hashing and cuckoo hashing move existing keys around in the array to make room for the new key.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] This gives better maximum search times than the methods based on probing.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] A critical influence on performance of an open addressing hash table is the *load factor*; that is, the proportion of the slots in the array that are used.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] As the load factor increases towards 100%, the number of probes that may be required to find or insert a given key rises dramatically.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] Once the table becomes full, probing algorithms may even fail to terminate.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] Even with good hash functions, load factors are normally limited to 80%.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] A poor hash function can exhibit poor performance even at very low load factors by generating significant clustering, especially with the simplest linear addressing method.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] Generally typical load factors with most open addressing methods are 50%, while separate chaining typically can use up to 100%.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] The following pseudocode is an implementation of an open addressing hash table with linear probing and single-slot stepping, a common approach that is effective if the hash function is good.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] Each of the **lookup**, **set** and **remove** functions use a common internal function **find_slot** to locate the array slot that either does or should contain a given key.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] operation to insert all the elements of the old array into the new larger array.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] , for example by doubling the old array size.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] For all records in a cluster, there must be no vacant slots between their natural hash position and their current position (else lookups will terminate before finding the record).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] is a vacant slot that might be invalidating this property for subsequent records in the cluster.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] would naturally land in the hash table if there were no collisions.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] Another technique for removal is simply to mark the slot as deleted.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] However this eventually requires rebuilding the table simply to remove deleted records.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] The methods above provide *O*(1) updating and removal of existing records, with occasional rebuilding if the high-water mark of the table size grows.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] The *O*(1) remove method above is only possible in linearly probed hash tables with single-slot stepping.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] In the case where many records are to be deleted in one operation, marking the slots for deletion and later rebuilding may be more efficient.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] Here *n* is the number of elements in the table, *m* the table size, $\alpha =n/m$ the load factor, $U_{n}$ the number of probes in an unsuccessful search and $S_{n}$ the number of probes in a successful search.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/open-addressing] Note that the expectation deteriorates to infinity when the load factor approaches 1.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/quadratic-probing] Quadratic probing is often recommended as an alternative to linear probing because it incurs less clustering.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/quadratic-probing] Quadratic probing exhibits better locality of reference than many other hash table such as chaining; however, for queries, quadratic probing does not have as good locality as linear probing, causing the latter to be faster in some settings.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/quadratic-probing] Quadratic probing was first introduced by Ward Douglas Maurer in 1968.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/quadratic-probing] Several subsequent variations of the data structure were proposed in the 1970s in order to guarantee that the probe sequence hits every slot without cycling prematurely.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/quadratic-probing] Quadratic probing is widely believed to avoid the clustering effects that make linear probing slow at high load factors.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/quadratic-probing] It serves as the basis for many widely used high-performance hash-tables, including Google's open-source Abseil hash table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/quadratic-probing] It is conjectured that quadratic probing, when filled to $1-\epsilon$ full, supports insertions in expected time $O(\epsilon ^{-1})$ .
[src:robin-hood-hashing/quadratic-probing] Proving this, or even proving *any* non-trivial time bound for quadratic probing remains open.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/quadratic-probing] The closest result, due to Kuszmaul and Xi, shows that, at load factors of less than $\approx 0.089$ , insertions take $O(1)$ expected time.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/quadratic-probing] Let *h*(*k*) be a hash function that maps an element *k* to an integer in [0, *m*−1], where *m* is the size of the table.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/quadratic-probing] For a given hash table, the values of *c*1 and *c*2 remain constant.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/quadratic-probing] If the sign of the offset is alternated (e.g. +1, −4, +9, −16, etc.), and if the number of buckets is a prime number p congruent to 3 modulo 4 (e.g.
[src:robin-hood-hashing/quadratic-probing] 3, 7, 11, 19, 23, 31, etc.), then the first p offsets will be unique (modulo p ).
[src:robin-hood-hashing/quadratic-probing] In other words, a permutation of 0 through $p-1$ is obtained, and, consequently, a free bucket will always be found as long as at least one exists.
